@Node "ACTIVATE" "termRexx.guide/ACTIVATE"
@Next "ADDITEM"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The ACTIVATE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     ACTIVATE

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     De-iconifies the program, brings the main window to the front and
     makes it active.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     The program can be put to sleep using the @{"DEACTIVATE" Link "DEACTIVATE"} command, to
     bring it back to proper operation, use the @{b}ACTIVATE@{ub} command. If
     this command is invoked while the program is not asleep, it will
     cause the main window to be brought to the front and activated.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* This is how the main programm can be (re-)activated: */

          ACTIVATE


@EndNode

@Node "ADDITEM" "termRexx.guide/ADDITEM"
@Next "BAUD"
@Prev "ACTIVATE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The ADDITEM command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     ADDITEM [To] <Upload|Download|Dial|Wait> [Before|After] [Command
     <Command for trap list>] [Response <Response text>] [Phone <Entry
     number, name or wildcard pattern>] [Name <Name>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TO/A,BEFORE/S,AFTER/S,RESPONSE/K,COMMAND/K,PHONE/K/F,NAME/K/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Inserts an item (a name, a phone number, text, etc.) before or
     after the currently selected list item.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     `term' maintains a number of lists, these are:
    @{b}Upload list@{ub}
          The list of files to be uploaded.

    @{b}Download list@{ub}
          The list of files the program has downloaded.

    @{b}Dial list@{ub}
          The list of phone numbers or phone book entries to be dialed.

    @{b}Wait list@{ub}
          The list of texts the @{"WAIT" Link "WAIT"} command is to wait for.

     New items can be added to the list with the @{b}ADDITEM@{ub} command. The
     upload list expects the names of files the @{"SENDFILE" Link "SENDFILE"} command is to
     transfer. It makes little sense to add files names to the download
     list as the `term' main program maintains it and adds the names of
     files received to it, but it is still possible. The wait list
     expects text lines the @{"WAIT" Link "WAIT"} command will look for in the terminal
     input stream.  A wait list entry added using the @{b}RESPONSE@{ub} keyword
     will if found in the input data stream cause the response text to
     be immediately sent to the remote.  @{i}Note: a wait list entry to
     make use of the @{b}RESPONSE@{ub} keyword will be handled by the @{"WAIT" Link "WAIT"}
     command, the ARexx script will not notice if this list entry was
     found or not.@{ui}

     The dial list accepts a number of different parameters:
    @{b}Phonebook entry numbers@{ub}
          These are passed using the @{b}Phone@{ub} parameter which should be a
          numeric value as it is used as an index to pick the
          corresponding entry from the phone book.

    @{b}Phonebook entry names@{ub}
          These are also passed using the @{b}Phone@{ub} parameter which can be a
          proper name or a wildcard pattern.

    @{b}Phone numbers@{ub}
          These are passed using the @{b}Name@{ub} parameter.

     List item can be inserted before or after the currently selected
     list item (see @{"SELECTITEM" Link "SELECTITEM"} command). The default is to insert them
     after the currently selected list item.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable result codes. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Get a file name from the user. */

          REQUESTFILE TITLE '"Select a file to upload"'

          /* Add the file name to the upload list. */

          IF rc = 0 THEN ADDITEM TO upload NAME result

          /* Add phonebook entry #2 to the dial list. */

          ADDITEM TO dial PHONE 2

          /* Add all phonebook entries whose names start
           * with an `a' to the dial list.
           */

          ADDITEM TO dial PHONE a#?

          /* Add a plain phone number to the dial list. */

          ADDITEM TO dial NAME 424242


@EndNode

@Node "BAUD" "termRexx.guide/BAUD"
@Next "BEEPSCREEN"
@Prev "ADDITEM"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The BAUD command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     BAUD [Rate] <Transfer speed in bits per second>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     RATE/A/N

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line transfer speed

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line transfers speed to some defined value. The
     rate parameter passed in will be matched against all valid BPS
     rates supported by `term', the closest value will be used.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the old baud value.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Change the serial transfer speed to 2400 bps. */

          BAUD 2400


@EndNode

@Node "BEEPSCREEN" "termRexx.guide/BEEPSCREEN"
@Next "CALLMENU"
@Prev "BAUD"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The BEEPSCREEN command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     BEEPSCREEN

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     `Beeps' the terminal screen.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Invokes a bell signal, as configured in the program settings.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Invoke a bell signal. */

          BEEPSCREEN


@EndNode

@Node "CALLMENU" "termRexx.guide/CALLMENU"
@Next "CAPTURE"
@Prev "BEEPSCREEN"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CALLMENU command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CALLMENU [Title] <Title text or wildcard pattern>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TITLE/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Invokes the function associated with a menu item.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Calls a pull-down menu function just as if the user had selected it
     using the mouse. The @{b}Title@{ub} parameter can be any valid menu item
     name or a wildcard pattern. In the latter case, only the first
     menu item to match the pattern will be called.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If no matching menu item was to be found.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Invoke the `About...' menu item. */

          CALLMENU abou#?


@EndNode

@Node "CAPTURE" "termRexx.guide/CAPTURE"
@Next "CLEAR"
@Prev "CALLMENU"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CAPTURE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CAPTURE [To] <Printer|File> [Append|Overwrite|Skip] [Name <File
     name>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TO/A,APPEND/S,OVERWRITE/S,SKIP/S,NAME/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Starts a file or printer capture.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     If a capture is not already in progress will open a capture file
     or start capturing incoming terminal text to the printer. If the
     @{b}File@{ub} argument is given and the @{b}Name@{ub} parameter is omitted, will
     prompt for the name of a file to capture to.

     If to capture to a given file, will append the captured text. If
     user is to select a file to capture to, will ask whether to append
     the text to the file or to overwrite it.

     The command will not prompt the user to confirm whether an
     existing file should be overwritten, etc. if one of the following
     options are in effect:

    @{b}APPEND@{ub}
          If the named file exists, append the new capture data to it.

    @{b}OVERWRITE@{ub}
          If the named file exists, delete it before adding new capture
          data to it.

    @{b}SKIP@{ub}
          If the named file exists, don't overwrite it. Do not open the
          capture file.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     In case user was to select a file and aborted the selection.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Open a named capture file. */

          CAPTURE TO file NAME 'ram:capture file'

          /* Close the capture file, ask the user for a file name. */

          CLOSE FILE
          CAPTURE TO file

          /* Capture to the printer. */

          CAPTURE TO printer


@EndNode

@Node "CLEAR" "termRexx.guide/CLEAR"
@Next "CLEARSCREEN"
@Prev "CAPTURE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CLEAR command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CLEAR [From] <Upload|Download|Dial|Wait|Buffer> [Force]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FROM/A,FORCE/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Clears the contents of a global list or the text buffer.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     This command serves to clear the contents of the lists to be
     maintained using the @{"ADDITEM" Link "ADDITEM"}, @{"REMITEM" Link "REMITEM"}, @{"SELECTITEM" Link "SELECTITEM"}, etc. commands
     and to purge the contents of the text buffer. In the latter case
     the program will prompt for confirmation in case the buffer still
     holds any lines. This confirmation can be suppressed by using the
     @{b}Force@{ub} parameter.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     In case the user did not confirm to clear the buffer.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Clear the wait list. */

          CLEAR FROM wait

          /* Clear the buffer, ask for a confirmation. */

          CLEAR FROM buffer

          /* If no confirmation was given, clear it by force. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN CLEAR FROM buffer FORCE


@EndNode

@Node "CLEARSCREEN" "termRexx.guide/CLEARSCREEN"
@Next "CLOSE"
@Prev "CLEAR"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CLEARSCREEN command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CLEARSCREEN

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Clears the terminal screen

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Clears the terminal screen and positions the cursor in the top
     left corner.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Clear the terminal screen. */

          CLEARSCREEN


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSE" "termRexx.guide/CLOSE"
@Next "CLOSEDEVICE"
@Prev "CLEARSCREEN"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CLOSE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CLOSE [From] <Printer|File|All>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FROM/A

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Terminates file and/or printer capture.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Terminates a capture process as started with the @{"CAPTURE" Link "CAPTURE"} command.
     Will terminate printer capture, file capture or both.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Terminate both file and printer capture. */

          CLOSE ALL


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSEDEVICE" "termRexx.guide/CLOSEDEVICE"
@Next "CLOSEREQUESTER"
@Prev "CLOSE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CLOSEDEVICE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CLOSEDEVICE

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Release the current serial device driver

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Frees the serial device driver for use with other applications.
     The driver can be reopened (or a different device driver can be
     selected) using the @{"OPENDEVICE" Link "OPENDEVICE"} command.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Release the serial device driver, all serial I/O
           * will be halted.
           */

          CLOSEDEVICE


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSEREQUESTER" "termRexx.guide/CLOSEREQUESTER"
@Next "DEACTIVATE"
@Prev "CLOSEDEVICE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The CLOSEREQUESTER command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     CLOSEREQUESTER

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Closes the currently open requester window

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Will close any currently open requester window, such as the
     dialing window, the phone book, the serial settings window, etc.
     Will not close windows such as the file transfer window or the
     text/numeric input windows.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Close the currently open requester window,
           * whatever it may be.
           */

          CLOSEREQUESTER


@EndNode

@Node "DEACTIVATE" "termRexx.guide/DEACTIVATE"
@Next "DELAY"
@Prev "CLOSEREQUESTER"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The DEACTIVATE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     DEACTIVATE

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Iconifies the program.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Puts the application to sleep. Requires Workbench to be running,
     so an AppIcon can be put on the Workbench backdrop. This command
     will be ignored if the application has already been put to sleep.
     To wake the application up, use the @{"ACTIVATE" Link "ACTIVATE"} command.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Iconify the program. */

          DEACTIVATE


@EndNode

@Node "DELAY" "termRexx.guide/DELAY"
@Next "DIAL"
@Prev "DEACTIVATE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The DELAY command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     DELAY [MIC|MICROSECONDS <Number>] [[SEC|SECONDS] <Number>]
     [MIN|MINUTES <Number>] [QUIET]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     MIC=MICROSECONDS/K/N,SEC=SECONDS/N,MIN=MINUTES/K/N,QUIET/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Delays program execution for a couple of microseconds, seconds and
     minutes.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Will cause both the program to make the call and the application
     to wait for a certain period of time. Unless the @{b}QUIET@{ub} option is
     in effect will process and display data received from the serial
     line.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If command was aborted before the timeout had elapsed.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Wait for five seconds. */

          DELAY 5

          /* Wait for one second and seven microseconds. */

          DELAY MIC 7 SEC 5


@EndNode

@Node "DIAL" "termRexx.guide/DIAL"
@Next "DUPLEX"
@Prev "DELAY"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The DIAL command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     DIAL [WAIT|SYNC] [[Num] <Phone number>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     WAIT=SYNC/S,NUM/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Dials the provided phone number. If no phone number was given,
     will dial the numbers and phone book entries stored in the dial
     list.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     This command will build a dialing list from the available sources
     and pass it to the dialing function which is to schedule the
     dialing process and perform any login-actions. Available sources
     are the @{b}Num@{ub} parameter which will cause the command to dial only
     this single number or the dial list whose contents will be used if
     the @{b}Num@{ub} parameter is omitted.

     If the @{b}WAIT@{ub} parameter is used the command will wait until a
     connection is made. If the parameter is not use this command will
     return as soon as the dialing process has been initiated.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If no connection was to be made.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Dial a single phone number. */

          DIAL 424242

          /* Wait a bit and abort the dialing process. */

          DELAY 5
          CLOSEREQUESTER

          /* Clear the dialing list, then add all the phonebook entries
           * to the list.
           */

          CLEAR FROM dial
          ADDITEM TO dial PHONE #?

          /* Dial the dial list. */

          DIAL WAIT

          /* Did we get a connection? */

          IF RC == 0 THEN SEND TEXT "Ack!\r"


@EndNode

@Node "DUPLEX" "termRexx.guide/DUPLEX"
@Next "EXECTOOL"
@Prev "DIAL"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The DUPLEX command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     DUPLEX [Full|Half|Echo]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FULL/S,HALF=ECHO/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line duplex mode.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line duplex mode, this can be either full duplex
     or half duplex (local echo).

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the old duplex value.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable local terminal echo. */

          DUPLEX ECHO


@EndNode

@Node "EXECTOOL" "termRexx.guide/EXECTOOL"
@Next "FAULT"
@Prev "DUPLEX"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The EXECTOOL command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     EXECTOOL [Console] [Async] [Port] [Command] <File name>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     CONSOLE/S,ASYNC/S,PORT/S,COMMAND/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Executes a program.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Will load and execute an AmigaDOS program. The @{b}Console@{ub} parameter
     will cause an output file or window to be opened, the @{b}Async@{ub}
     parameter will cause the command to return as soon as the
     execution process has been launched. The @{b}Port@{ub} parameter will cause
     the current ARexx host port name to be passed to the tool on the
     command line.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Launch the `Dir' command. */

          EXECTOOL CONSOLE COMMAND 'dir c:'


@EndNode

@Node "FAULT" "termRexx.guide/FAULT"
@Next "GETATTR"
@Prev "EXECTOOL"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The FAULT command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     FAULT [Code] <Error code>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     CODE/A/N

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Returns the descriptive text associated with an error code as
     returned by `term'.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     `term' will return error codes in the @{b}term.lasterror@{ub} variable. In
     order to get the descriptive text associated with an error code,
     use this command.  All internal Rexx and AmigaDOS errors codes are
     supported as well as the error codes special to `term'.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     The error description associated with the error code.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Get the text associated with error #1001. */

          FAULT 1001

          /* Output the result. */

          SAY result


@EndNode

@Node "GETATTR" "termRexx.guide/GETATTR"
@Next "GETCLIP"
@Prev "FAULT"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The GETATTR command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     GETATTR [Object] <Name> [Field] <Name> [Stem <Name>] [Var <Name>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     OBJECT/A,FIELD,STEM/K,VAR/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Obtains information on an application attribute.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Obtains information on an object, if possible will store it in the
     @{b}result@{ub} variable. If a stem or simple variable name is given using
     the @{b}Stem@{ub} or @{b}Var@{ub} parameters will store the information in this
     variable.  If no @{b}Field@{ub} parameter is given, will store the entire
     object contents which requires that the @{b}Stem@{ub} parameter is given.
     For a list of valid attributes see the section entitled @{"Attributes" Link "Attributes"}.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns information either in @{b}result@{ub} variable or in the supplied
     @{b}Stem@{ub} or @{b}Var@{ub} variable.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Query the name of the ARexx host we are communicating with. */

          GETATTR OBJECT term FIELD arexx

          /* Output the result. */

          SAY result

          /* Same as above, but using a different syntax. */

          GETATTR term.arexx
          SAY result

          /* Store the entire contents of the phone book in a
           * stem variable.
           */

          GETATTR phonebook STEM book

          /* Output the phonebook contents. */

          SAY 'phone book contains' book.count 'entries'

          DO i = 0 TO book.count - 1
             SAY 'entry #' i

             SAY 'name    :' book.i.name
             SAY 'number  :' book.i.number
             SAY 'comment :' book.i.commenttext
             SAY 'username:' book.i.username
          END i


@EndNode

@Node "GETCLIP" "termRexx.guide/GETCLIP"
@Next "GOONLINE"
@Prev "GETATTR"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The GETCLIP command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     GETCLIP [Unit <Number>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     UNIT/K/N

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Retrieves the contents of the clipboard.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Obtains the contents of the clipboard and returns it in the @{b}result@{ub}
     variable. Will optionally read from the given clipboard unit, but
     uses the unit number selected in the application settings by
     default. @{i}Note that a string returned can be up to 65,536
     characters long!@{ui}

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Contents of the clipboard if it contains any text.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If clipboard does not contain any text.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Get the primary clipboard contents. */

          GETCLIP

          /* Output the contents. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'clipboard does not contain any text'
          ELSE
             SAY result


@EndNode

@Node "GOONLINE" "termRexx.guide/GOONLINE"
@Next "HANGUP"
@Prev "GETCLIP"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The GOONLINE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     GOONLINE

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Cause `term' to go into online state.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     After this command is processed `term' will immediately go into
     online state. If the carrier signal is to be checked and no signal
     is present `term' will drop into offline state right away.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Go into online state. */

          GOONLINE


@EndNode

@Node "HANGUP" "termRexx.guide/HANGUP"
@Next "HELP"
@Prev "GOONLINE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The HANGUP command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     HANGUP

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Hang up the serial line.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Hangs up the serial line, executes logoff and cleanup operations.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Hang up the line, whether the program is online or not. */

          HANGUP


@EndNode

@Node "HELP" "termRexx.guide/HELP"
@Next "OPEN"
@Prev "HANGUP"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The HELP command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     HELP [[Command] <Name>] [Prompt]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     COMMAND,PROMPT/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Returns the template of a command or invokes the online help
     system.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     This command will either return the template associated with a
     `term' ARexx command specified using the @{b}Command@{ub} parameter or
     invoke the AmigaGuide(tm) help system.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Command template if requested.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Query the template associated with the `selectitem' command. */

          HELP selectitem

          /* Output the result. */

          SAY result

          /* Invoke the online help. */

          HELP PROMPT


@EndNode

@Node "OPEN" "termRexx.guide/OPEN"
@Next "OPENDEVICE"
@Prev "HELP"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The OPEN command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     OPEN [Name <File name>] [TO] <Translations|Functionkeys|Cursorkeys|
     Fastmacros|Hotkeys|Speech|Sound|Buffer|Configuration|Phone>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NAME/K,TO/A

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Reads data from a disk file.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     This command reads the contents of a disk file and stores the
     information either in the configuration, the phone book or the
     text buffer. If text is read into the text buffer it will be
     appended to the existing text. If no file name is given will
     prompt the user to select a file.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user was requested to select a file and cancelled the selection.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Load the configuration from a file. */

          OPEN NAME 'ram:term.prefs' TO configuration

          /* Add text to the text buffer. */

          OPEN TO buffer


@EndNode

@Node "OPENDEVICE" "termRexx.guide/OPENDEVICE"
@Next "OPENREQUESTER"
@Prev "OPEN"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The OPENDEVICE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     OPENDEVICE [Name <Device name>] [Unit <Number>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NAME/K,UNIT/K/N

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     (Re-)Opens the serial device driver.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     (Re-)Opens the previously released (see @{"CLOSEDEVICE" Link "CLOSEDEVICE"} command) device
     driver or a different device driver/unit if the corresponding
     @{b}Device@{ub} and @{b}Unit@{ub} parameters are given.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the old device name and unit number.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Request command results. */
          options results

          /* Release the serial device driver. */

          CLOSEDEVICE

          /* Open a different device driver. */

          OPENDEVICE DEVICE 'duart.device' UNIT 5

          /* Tell the name of the old device driver,
           * and unit number, e.g. "serial.device/0"
           */

          say RESULT


@EndNode

@Node "OPENREQUESTER" "termRexx.guide/OPENREQUESTER"
@Next "PARITY"
@Prev "OPENDEVICE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The OPENREQUESTER command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     OPENREQUESTER [REQUESTER]
     <Serial|Modem|Screen|Terminal|Emulation|Clipboard|






     Capture|Commands|Misc|Path|Transfer|Translations|Functionkeys|Cursorkeys|
     Fastmacros|Hotkeys|Speech|Sound|Phone>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     REQUESTER/A

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Opens a requester window.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Opens a requester window. Only a single window can be open at a
     time.  The window opened can be closed using the @{"CLOSEREQUESTER" Link "CLOSEREQUESTER"}
     command.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Open the phonebook window. */

          OPENREQUESTER phone


@EndNode

@Node "PARITY" "termRexx.guide/PARITY"
@Next "PASTECLIP"
@Prev "OPENREQUESTER"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The PARITY command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     PARITY [Even|Odd|None|Mark|Space]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     EVEN/S,ODD/S,NONE/S,MARK/S,SPACE/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line parity mode.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line parity mode.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the old parity mode.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Set the parity mode. */

          PARITY NONE


@EndNode

@Node "PASTECLIP" "termRexx.guide/PASTECLIP"
@Next "PRINT"
@Prev "PARITY"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The PASTECLIP command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     PASTECLIP [Unit <Number>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     UNIT/K/N

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Feed the contents of the clipboard into the input stream.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Feeds the contents of the clipboard into the input stream. Obtains
     the data either from the given clipboard unit or from the default
     unit configured in the program settings.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If clipboard does not contain any text.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Paste the contents of clipboard #2. */

          PASTECLIP UNIT 2


@EndNode

@Node "PRINT" "termRexx.guide/PRINT"
@Next "PROCESSIO"
@Prev "PASTECLIP"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The PRINT command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     PRINT [From]
     <Screentext|Clipboard|Buffer|Dial|Wait|Upload|Download> [TO <File
     name>] [Serial|Modem|Screen|Terminal|User|Comment| Size|Date|Attr]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FROM/A,TO/K,SERIAL/S,MODEM/S,SCREEN/S,TERMINAL/S,USER/S,
     COMMENT/S,SIZE/S,DATE/S,ATTR/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Prints the contents of the screen, the clipboard, the textbuffer
     or one of the lists.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Outputs the contents of the screen, the clipboard, the textbuffer
     or one of the lists (see @{"ADDITEM" Link "ADDITEM"} command) to a file or the
     printer. If the @{b}To@{ub} parameter is omitted, will output the data to
     the printer. The parameters @{b}Serial@{ub} through @{b}Attr@{ub} control what will
     be printed:
    @{b}Screentext, Clipboard, Buffer, Wait list@{ub}
          Options have no effect on the output.

    @{b}Dial list@{ub}
          Responds to the @{b}Serial@{ub}, @{b}Modem@{ub}, @{b}Screen@{ub}, @{b}Terminal@{ub}, @{b}User@{ub} and
          @{b}Comment@{ub} parameters. The printout will contain information on
          the corresponding settings.

    @{b}Upload list, Download list@{ub}
          Responds to the @{b}Comment@{ub}, @{b}Size@{ub}, @{b}Date@{ub} and @{b}Attr@{ub} parameters. The
          printout will contain information on the corresponding file
          attributes. @{i}Note: if any of these parameters are given, only
          the base file names will be printed along with the
          corresponding information.@{ui}

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancelled print operation.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Clear the dialing list, then add the entire phone book to it. */

          CLEAR dial
          additem to dial phone #?

          /* Send the contents of the dial list to a disk file. */

          PRINT FROM dial TO 'ram:phonebook' SERIAL MODEM SCREEN...
          ...TERMINAL USER COMMENT


@EndNode

@Node "PROCESSIO" "termRexx.guide/PROCESSIO"
@Next "PROTOCOL"
@Prev "PRINT"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The PROCESSIO command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     PROCESSIO <On|Off>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ON/S,OFF/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Turns serial I/O processing on or off.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Usually, the `term' main program processes incoming data from the
     serial line, i.e. text is displayed in the terminal window or data
     transfers are started. This can interfere with custom I/O
     processing, such as done by an ARexx program which wants to
     receive and process all incoming serial data, without getting
     interrupted by the main program. For an application example see
     @{"WAIT" Link "WAIT"}.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the old PROCESSIO value.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Turn off I/O processing. */

          PROCESSIO OFF


@EndNode

@Node "PROTOCOL" "termRexx.guide/PROTOCOL"
@Next "PUTCLIP"
@Prev "PROCESSIO"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The PROTOCOL command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     PROTOCOL [None|RTSCTS|RTSCTSDTR]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NONE/S,RTSCTS/S,RTSCTSDTR/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line handshaking protocol.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sets the serial line handshaking protocol. See the main program
     documentation for details.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the old protocol mode.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Set the handshaking protocol. */

          PROTOCOL NONE


@EndNode

@Node "PUTCLIP" "termRexx.guide/PUTCLIP"
@Next "QUIT"
@Prev "PROTOCOL"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The PUTCLIP command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     PUTCLIP [Unit <Unit>] [TEXT] <Text to store>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     UNIT/K/N,TEXT/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Stores text in the clipboard.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Stores the provided text in the clipboard. Will store it in the
     given clipboard unit if the @{b}Unit@{ub} parameter is given. Will use the
     unit number configured in the program settings otherwise.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Store a short string in the clipboard. Note: can
           * only be up to 65,536 characters long.
           */

          PUTCLIP 'hello sailor!'


@EndNode

@Node "QUIT" "termRexx.guide/QUIT"
@Next "READ"
@Prev "PUTCLIP"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The QUIT command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     QUIT [Force]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FORCE/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Terminates the application.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Terminates program execution, will ask for a confirmation to leave
     unless the @{b}Force@{ub} parameter is used. @{i}Caution: this command may fail
     if there are still output windows open on the `term' screen.@{ui}

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user did not confirm termination.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Try to terminate the program, ask for confirmation. */

          QUIT

          /* If no confirmation was given terminate by force. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN QUIT FORCE


@EndNode

@Node "READ" "termRexx.guide/READ"
@Next "RECEIVEFILE"
@Prev "QUIT"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The READ command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     READ [Num <Number of bytes>] [CR] [Noecho] [Verbatim] [Timeout
     <Seconds>] [Terminator <Character>] [[Prompt] <Prompt text>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}

     NUM/K/N,CR/S,NOECHO/S,VERBATIM/S,TIMEOUT/K/N,TERMINATOR/K,PROMPT/K/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Reads a number of bytes or a string from the serial line.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     If @{b}Num@{ub} parameter is given will read a number of bytes from the
     serial line (@{i}note: only a maximum of 65,536 bytes can be read@{ui}).
     The command will return when the read request has been satisfied,
     the timeout (settable using the @{"TIMEOUT" Link "TIMEOUT"} command) has elapsed or
     the command was aborted.

     If the @{b}CR@{ub} parameter is given will handle simple line editing
     functions (@{b}Backspace@{ub}, @{b}Control-X@{ub}) and return a string as soon as
     the @{b}Carriage return@{ub} key is pressed, the timeout (settable using
     the @{"TIMEOUT" Link "TIMEOUT"} command) has elapsed or the command is aborted.

     The @{b}Noecho@{ub} parameter will cause `term' not to echo typed
     characters back to the remote. @{i}Note that in order to see any input
     on the local side the remote is to echo the characters typed back.@{ui}

     With the @{b}Timeout@{ub} parameter you can override the global timeout
     value (settable using the @{"TIMEOUT" Link "TIMEOUT"} command) for this command.

     The @{b}Terminator@{ub} parameter tells the command to stop when finding
     the given character in the input stream. For example, @{b}TERMINATOR
     "\n"@{ub} would tell the command to stop when finding the line feed
     character in the input stream.

     If present, the @{b}Prompt@{ub} text will be sent across the serial line,
     much the same as if it had been sent using the @{"SEND" Link "SEND"} command.

     This command pays attention to the current character translation
     table for incoming characters. If the characters are to be read
     without any changes made one has to use the @{b}Verbatim@{ub} parameter.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     The string read.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If command was cancelled, no input was made or, if the @{b}CR@{ub} parameter
     is used, the timeout elapsed.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Set the read timeout to five seconds. */

          TIMEOUT 5

          /* Read seven bytes. */

          READ NUM 7

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no data was read'
          ELSE
             SAY result

          /* Wait up to eight seconds to eight bytes to arrive. */

          READ TIMEOUT 8 NUM 8

          /* Turn the timeout off. */

          TIMEOUT OFF

          /* Prompt for input. */

          READ CR PROMPT 'Enter a line of text:'

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no input was made'
          ELSE
             SAY result


@EndNode

@Node "RECEIVEFILE" "termRexx.guide/RECEIVEFILE"
@Next "REDIAL"
@Prev "READ"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RECEIVEFILE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RECEIVEFILE [Mode <ASCII|Text|Binary>] [Name <File name>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     MODE/K,NAME/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Receive one or more files using the XPR protocol.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Receives one or more files using the currently configured XPR
     protocol.  The @{b}Mode@{ub} parameter determines the file transfer mode
     (either plain ASCII, Text mode or binary file mode), if omitted
     the file(s) will be received in binary mode. Some file transfer
     protocols do not require any file names to be given as they have
     their own means to determine the names of the files to be
     received. However, a file name parameter can be given. If omitted
     the file transfer protocol will prompt the user for a file name if
     necessary.

     The names of all files received are placed on the download list
     for processing. The list will be cleared before the transfer is
     started.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancelled file selection.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Start to receive a file in text mode. */

          RECEIVEFILE MODE text


@EndNode

@Node "REDIAL" "termRexx.guide/REDIAL"
@Next "REMITEM"
@Prev "RECEIVEFILE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REDIAL command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REDIAL

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Redials the numbers remaining in the currently configured dialing
     list.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Redials the numbers which still remain in the dialing list built
     either by the phone book or by the @{"DIAL" Link "DIAL"} command. @{i}Note that this
     command will return as soon as the dialing process is initiated.@{ui}

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If dialing list is empty.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Redial the list. */

          REDIAL

          /* Successful? */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN SAY 'dialing list is empty'


@EndNode

@Node "REMITEM" "termRexx.guide/REMITEM"
@Next "REQUESTFILE"
@Prev "REDIAL"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REMITEM command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REMITEM [From] <Upload|Download|Dial|Wait> [Name <Name or
     wildcard>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FROM/A,NAME/K/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Removes one or more items from a list.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Removes one or more items from a list. If no @{b}Name@{ub} parameter is
     given will remove the currently selected list item (selectable
     using the @{"SELECTITEM" Link "SELECTITEM"} command). The @{b}Name@{ub} parameter can be a proper
     name or a wildcard pattern.

     @{i}Note: Cannot remove named items from the dial list.@{ui}

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If no list item would match the name pattern.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Remove the currently selected item from the wait list. */

          REMITEM FROM wait

          /* Remove all items from the wait list which end with `z'. */

          REMITEM FROM wait NAME '#?z'


@EndNode

@Node "REQUESTFILE" "termRexx.guide/REQUESTFILE"
@Next "REQUESTNOTIFY"
@Prev "REMITEM"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REQUESTFILE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REQUESTFILE [Title <Title text>] [Path <Path name>] [File <File
     name>] [Pattern <Wildcard pattern>] [Multi] [Stem|Name <Variable
     name>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TITLE/K,PATH/K,FILE/K,PATTERN/K,MULTI/S,STEM=NAME/K

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Requests one or more file names from the user.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Requests one or more file names from the user. Will present a file
     requester with given title text and preset path, file name and
     pattern values. If only a single file name is to be requested will
     place the result in the @{b}result@{ub} variable. The @{b}Multi@{ub} parameter
     allows multiple files to be selected, the number of files selected
     and the file names will be placed in the variable specified using
     the @{b}Stem@{ub} parameter.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     The name of the file selected will be placed in the @{b}result@{ub}
     variable. If multiple file were selected, will place the following
     information in the supplied stem variable:
    @{b}<Variable name>.COUNT@{ub}
          The number of files selected.

    @{b}<Variable name>.0 through <Variable name>.n-1@{ub}
          The file names selected.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancelled selection.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Request a single file name from the user. */

          REQUESTFILE TITLE '"select a file"'

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no file was selected'
          ELSE
             SAY result

          /* Request several files. */

          REQUESTFILE TITLE 'select several files' MULTI STEM names

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no files were selected'
          ELSE DO
             SAY 'files selected:' names.count

             DO i = 0 TO names.count - 1
                SAY names.i
             END
          END


@EndNode

@Node "REQUESTNOTIFY" "termRexx.guide/REQUESTNOTIFY"
@Next "REQUESTNUMBER"
@Prev "REQUESTFILE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REQUESTNOTIFY command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REQUESTNOTIFY [Title <Title text>] [Prompt] <Prompt text>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TITLE/K,PROMPT/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Notify the user with a message.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Opens a requester to notify the user, the prompt text can include
     line feed characters (@{b}'0A'X@{ub}), the user will be able to answer the
     requester by clicking on a @{b}Continue@{ub} button.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Notify the user. */

          REQUESTNOTIFY TITLE '"Important information"' ...
          ...PROMPT 'This message is important'


@EndNode

@Node "REQUESTNUMBER" "termRexx.guide/REQUESTNUMBER"
@Next "REQUESTRESPONSE"
@Prev "REQUESTNOTIFY"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REQUESTNUMBER command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REQUESTNUMBER [Default <Default number>] [Prompt <Prompt text>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     DEFAULT/K/N,PROMPT/K/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Requests a numeric value from the user

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Requests a numeric value from the user, will display the provided
     prompt text or a default text and present the provided default
     number, so user can simply hit return to accept the defaults.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     The number the has entered.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancelled requester.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Requester a single number. */

          REQUESTNUMBER DEFAULT 42 PROMPT 'Enter the answer'

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no number was entered'
          ELSE
             SAY result


@EndNode

@Node "REQUESTRESPONSE" "termRexx.guide/REQUESTRESPONSE"
@Next "REQUESTSTRING"
@Prev "REQUESTNUMBER"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REQUESTRESPONSE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REQUESTRESPONSE [Title <Title text>] [Options <Options string>]
     [Prompt] <Prompt text>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     TITLE/K,OPTIONS/K,PROMPT/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Request a response from user.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Requests a response from the user, uses provided title and prompt
     text and a number of options. If no options are specified will use
     @{b}Yes|No@{ub} as the defaults.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     For @{b}Options@{ub} passed as @{b}Yes|Perhaps|No@{ub} will return 1 for @{b}Yes@{ub}, 2 for
     @{b}Perhaps@{ub} and return a warning for @{b}No@{ub}.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user selected negative choice.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Request a response. */

          REQUESTRESPONSE PROMPT 'Are you indecisive?' ...
          ...OPTIONS '"Yes|Don't know|No"'

          /* Look at the response. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'Not indecisive'
          ELSE DO
             IF result = 0 THEN
                SAY 'Indecisive'
             ELSE
                SAY 'Probably indecisive'
          END


@EndNode

@Node "REQUESTSTRING" "termRexx.guide/REQUESTSTRING"
@Next "RESET"
@Prev "REQUESTRESPONSE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The REQUESTSTRING command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     REQUESTSTRING [Secret] [Default <String>] [Prompt <Text>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     SECRET/S,DEFAULT/K,PROMPT/K/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Requests a string from the user.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Requests a string from the user, will display the provided prompt
     text or a default text and present the provided default string, so
     user can simply hit return to accept the defaults.

     If the @{b}Secret@{ub} parameter is provided, will not display the
     characters typed.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     The text the user entered.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancelled the requester.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Request a secret string. */

          REQUESTSTRING SECRET DEFAULT '"hello sailor!"' ...
          ...PROMPT 'Enter secret message'

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no text was entered'
          ELSE
             SAY result


@EndNode

@Node "RESET" "termRexx.guide/RESET"
@Next "RESETSCREEN"
@Prev "REQUESTSTRING"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RESET command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RESET [Clear][Styles][Text][Timer]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     CLEAR/S,STYLES/S,TEXT/S,TIMER/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     This is a superset of all the RESET commands.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     See @{"RESETSTYLES" Link "RESETSTYLES"}, @{"RESETTEXT" Link "RESETTEXT"}, @{"RESETSCREEN" Link "RESETSCREEN"}, @{"RESETTIMER" Link "RESETTIMER"}.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Reset the terminal screen. */

          RESET CLEAR


@EndNode

@Node "RESETSCREEN" "termRexx.guide/RESETSCREEN"
@Next "RESETSTYLES"
@Prev "RESET"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RESETSCREEN command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RESETSCREEN

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Resets the terminal screen to defaults.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Resets the terminal screen to defaults, this includes clearing the
     screen, moving the cursor to the home position and resetting text,
     text rendering styles and colours.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Reset the terminal screen. */

          RESETSCREEN


@EndNode

@Node "RESETSTYLES" "termRexx.guide/RESETSTYLES"
@Next "RESETTEXT"
@Prev "RESETSCREEN"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RESETSTYLES command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RESETSTYLES

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Resets the text rendering styles to defaults.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Resets the text rendering styles to defaults, turning off inverse
     video, boldface, italics, etc. modes.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Reset the text rendering styles. */

          RESETSTYLES


@EndNode

@Node "RESETTEXT" "termRexx.guide/RESETTEXT"
@Next "RESETTIMER"
@Prev "RESETSTYLES"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RESETTEXT command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RESETTEXT

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Reset the terminal text to defaults.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Reset the terminal text to defaults, this includes switching back
     from graphics text or G1 mode.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Reset the terminal text. */

          RESETTEXT


@EndNode

@Node "RESETTIMER" "termRexx.guide/RESETTIMER"
@Next "RX"
@Prev "RESETTEXT"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RESETTIMER command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RESETTIMER

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Reset the online timer.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     The online timer is reset to 00:00:00, regardless whether `term'
     is currently online or not.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Reset the online timer. */

          RESETTIMER


@EndNode

@Node "RX" "termRexx.guide/RX"
@Next "SAVE"
@Prev "RESETTIMER"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The RX command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     RX [Console] [Async] [Command] <Command name>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     CONSOLE/S,ASYNC/S,COMMAND/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Invokes an ARexx macro file.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Invokes an ARexx macro file, if @{b}Console@{ub} argument specified opens a
     console output window, else uses @{b}NIL:@{ub}, if @{b}Async@{ub} argument specified
     executes the macro asynchronously.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Launch the `term' command shell. */

          RX CONSOLE ASYNC 'term:cmdshell.term'


@EndNode

@Node "SAVE" "termRexx.guide/SAVE"
@Next "SAVEAS"
@Prev "RX"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SAVE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SAVE [From] <Translations|Functionkeys|
     Cursorkeys|Fastmacros|Hotkeys|Speech|
     Sound|Buffer|Configuration|Phone| Screentext|Screenimage>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     FROM/A

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Saves data to a disk file.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Saves data to a disk file, will prompt for a file name to save to.
     See @{"SAVEAS" Link "SAVEAS"} command for more information.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancels save operation.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Save the terminal screen contents to an
           * IFF-ILBM file.
           */

          SAVE FROM screenimage


@EndNode

@Node "SAVEAS" "termRexx.guide/SAVEAS"
@Next "SELECTITEM"
@Prev "SAVE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SAVEAS command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SAVEAS [Name <File name>] [From]
     <Translations|Functionkeys|Cursorkeys|
     Fastmacros|Hotkeys|Speech|Sound|Buffer|
     Configuration|Phone|Screentext| Screenimage>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NAME/K,FROM/A

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Saves data to a disk file.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Saves data to a disk file, will prompt for a filename to save to
     if none is provided. Will save either parts of the program
     configuration or the phone book contents (@{b}Phonebook@{ub} parameter),
     the contents of the terminal screen as plain ASCII text
     (@{b}Screentext@{ub} parameter) or the contents of the terminal
     screen as an IFF-ILBM-file (@{b}Screenimage@{ub} parameter).

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancels save operation.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Save the program configuration to a file. */

          SAVEAS NAME 'ram:term.prefs' FROM configuration


@EndNode

@Node "SELECTITEM" "termRexx.guide/SELECTITEM"
@Next "SEND"
@Prev "SAVEAS"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SELECTITEM command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SELECTITEM [Name <Name>] [From] <Upload|Download|Dial|Wait>
     [Next|Prev|Previous|Top|Bottom]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NAME/K,FROM/A,NEXT/S,PREV=PREVIOUS/S,TOP/S,BOTTOM/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Select an item from a list.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Selects an item from a list, returns the item name in the @{b}result@{ub}
     variable. The @{b}Top@{ub} parameter will select the first list item,
     @{b}Bottom@{ub} the last item. The @{b}Previous@{ub} parameter will select the
     previous list item, @{b}Next@{ub} the next successive item. Instead of
     using a positioning parameter, it is also possible to use a
     wildcard pattern or name with the @{b}Name@{ub} parameter. The first list
     item to match the name will be selected.

     @{i}Note: cannot be used with the dial list.@{ui}

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the list item in the @{b}result@{ub} variable.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If end of list reached.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Output the contents of the download list. */

          SELECTITEM FROM download TOP

          DO WHILE rc = 0
             SAY result
             SELECTITEM FROM download NEXT
          END


@EndNode

@Node "SEND" "termRexx.guide/SEND"
@Next "SENDBREAK"
@Prev "SELECTITEM"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SEND command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SEND [Noecho] [Local] [Literal] [Byte <ASCII code>] [Text] <Text>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NOECHO/S,LOCAL/S,LITERAL/S,BYTE/K/N,TEXT/A/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sends the provided text to the serial line, executes embedded
     command sequences.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sends the provided text to the serial line, executes embedded
     command sequences (see main program documentation). To send a
     single byte, use the @{b}Byte@{ub} parameter. The @{b}Noecho@{ub} parameter will
     suppress terminal output. The @{b}Local@{ub} parameter will cause the text
     to be output only locally in the terminal window, it will not be
     sent across the serial line. The @{b}Literal@{ub} parameter keeps `term'
     from interpreting any special characters, such as @{b}\r@{ub}, in the text
     to send and just transmits the text you passed in.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Send some text to the serial line. */

          SEND 'This is some text.\r\n'

          /* Send a single byte (a null) to the serial line. */

          SEND BYTE 0

          /* Execute an embedded command (send a break signal). */

          SEND '\x'


@EndNode

@Node "SENDBREAK" "termRexx.guide/SENDBREAK"
@Next "SENDFILE"
@Prev "SEND"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SENDBREAK command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SENDBREAK

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ,

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Send a break signal across the serial line.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Send a break signal across the serial line.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Send a break signal. */

          SENDBREAK


@EndNode

@Node "SENDFILE" "termRexx.guide/SENDFILE"
@Next "SETATTR"
@Prev "SENDBREAK"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SENDFILE command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SENDFILE [Mode <ASCII|Text|Binary>] [Names] {File names}

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     MODE/K,NAMES/M

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Transfers files using the currently selected file transfer
     protocol.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Transfers one or more files using the currently configured XPR
     protocol.  The @{b}Mode@{ub} parameter determines the file transfer mode
     (either plain ASCII, Text mode or binary file mode), if omitted
     the file(s) will be sent in binary mode. Some file transfer
     protocols do not require any file names to be given as they have
     their own means to determine the names of the files to be sent.
     However, a file name parameter can be given. If omitted the file
     transfer protocol will prompt the user for a file name if
     necessary. Several file names can be given if necessary, they will
     be transferred along with the file names stored in the upload
     list. The file transfer process will remove any files successfully
     transferred from the upload list, leaving only those behing which
     were not to be transferred correctly.

     Files whose names do not include a fully qualified path name are
     expected to reside in the default upload directory as specified in
     the main program paths settings.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If user cancels file selection.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Prompt for files to be uploaded. */

          SENDFILE

          /* Send a single file. */

          SENDFILE 'c:list'

          /* Clear the upload list, add a single file name. */

          CLEAR upload
          ADDITEM TO upload NAME 'c:dir'

          /* Transfer the file. */

          SENDFILE


@EndNode

@Node "SETATTR" "termRexx.guide/SETATTR"
@Next "SPEAK"
@Prev "SENDFILE"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The SETATTR command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     SETATTR [Object] <Name> [Field] <Name> [Stem <Name>] [Var <Name>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     OBJECT/A,FIELD,STEM/K,VAR

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets a certain application attribute.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sets a certain application attribute, retrieves the information
     from the supplied stem or simple variable. For a list of valid
     attributes, see the section entitled @{"Attributes" Link "Attributes"}.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Set the transfer speed. */

          SETATTR serialprefs baudrate 2400


@EndNode

@Node "SPEAK" "termRexx.guide/SPEAK"
@Next "STOPBITS"
