@Node "TEXTBUFFER" "termRexx.guide/TEXTBUFFER"
@Next "TIMEOUT"
@Prev "STOPBITS"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The TEXTBUFFER command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     TEXTBUFFER [Lock|Unlock]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     LOCK/S,UNLOCK/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Locks or unlocks the text buffer contents.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Locks or unlocks the text buffer contents, similar to the effect
     of the corresponding main menu entry.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Lock the text buffer. */

          TEXTBUFFER LOCK


@EndNode

@Node "TIMEOUT" "termRexx.guide/TIMEOUT"
@Next "TRAP"
@Prev "TEXTBUFFER"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The TIMEOUT command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     TIMEOUT [[Sec|Seconds] <Number>] [Off]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     SEC=SECONDS/N,OFF/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Sets the serial read timeout.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Sets the timeout the @{"WAIT" Link "WAIT"} and @{"READ" Link "READ"} commands will wait until they
     exit.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Set the read timeout. */

          TIMEOUT SEC 5


@EndNode

@Node "TRAP" "termRexx.guide/TRAP"
@Next "WAIT"
@Prev "TIMEOUT"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The TRAP command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     TRAP <On|Off>

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     ON/S,OFF/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Turns the trap list processing on or off.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     This command tells the main program whether it should process
     entries of the trap list when filtering input or not.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Ignore the trap list. */

          TRAP OFF


@EndNode

@Node "WAIT" "termRexx.guide/WAIT"
@Next "WINDOW"
@Prev "TRAP"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The WAIT command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     WAIT [Noecho] [Timeout <Seconds>] [[Text] <Text>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NOECHO/S,TIMEOUT/K/N,TEXT/F

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Waits for a certain sequence of characters to be received from the
     serial line.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Wait for text to be received from the serial line. If no text to
     wait for is provided wait for either item of the wait list to
     appear. The @{b}Noecho@{ub} parameter suppresses terminal output. @{i}Note that
     text comparison does not consider the case of characters (in
     respect to the ECMA Latin 1 character set).@{ui} As `term' has control
     over the incoming data stream before and after the @{b}WAIT@{ub} command is
     executed, it may `eat' and process data the @{b}WAIT@{ub} command ought to
     receive. In order to avoid this effect you can use the @{b}PROCESSIO@{ub}
     command (see @{"PROCESSIO" Link "PROCESSIO"}). For example, at the beginning of a
     program you could tell `term' to leave the incoming data stream
     alone with the @{b}PROCESSIO OFF@{ub} command, then invoke the @{b}WAIT@{ub} command
     as needed, and eventually when your program exits allow `term' to
     process incoming data with the @{b}PROCESSIO ON@{ub} command.

     With the @{b}Timeout@{ub} parameter you can override the global timeout
     value (settable using the @{"TIMEOUT" Link "TIMEOUT"} command) for this command.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     Returns the string found.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     If timeout has elapsed before any matching text was received.

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Enable command results. */

          OPTIONS RESULTS

          /* Set the read timeout. */

          TIMEOUT SEC 30

          /* Wait for a single line of text. */

          WAIT 'some text'

          /* Wait up to ten seconds for a single line of text. */

          WAIT TIMEOUT 10 'some more text'

          /* Clear the wait list, add a few items. */

          CLEAR wait
          ADDITEM TO wait NAME 'foo'
          ADDITEM TO wait NAME 'bar'

          /* Wait for the text to appear. */

          WAIT

          /* Output the result. */

          IF rc ~= 0 THEN
             SAY 'no text was received'
          ELSE
             SAY result


@EndNode

@Node "WINDOW" "termRexx.guide/WINDOW"
@Prev "WAIT"
@Toc "Commands"

@{u}The WINDOW command@{uu}

@{b}Format:@{ub}
     WINDOW [Names] {<Buffer|Review|Packet|Fastmacros|
     Status|Main|UploadQueue>} [Open|Close] [Activate] [Min|Max]
     [Front|Back] [Top|Bottom|Up|Down]

@{b}Template:@{ub}
     NAMES/A/M,OPEN/S,CLOSE/S,ACTIVATE/S,MIN/S,MAX/S,FRONT/S,BACK/S,
     TOP/S,BOTTOM/S,UP/S,DOWN/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}
     Manipulates the aspects of a window.

@{b}Specifications:@{ub}
     Manipulates the aspects of a window. Not all windows will support
     all available commands. The windows supported are:
    @{b}Buffer@{ub}
          The text buffer window and screen. Supports the @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Close@{ub},
          @{b}Activate@{ub} and @{b}Front@{ub} commands.

    @{b}Review@{ub}
          The review window. Supports the @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Close@{ub}, @{b}Activate@{ub}, @{b}Min@{ub},
          @{b}Max@{ub}, @{b}Front@{ub}, @{b}Back@{ub}, @{b}Top@{ub}, @{b}Bottom@{ub}, @{b}Up@{ub}, and @{b}Down@{ub} commands.

    @{b}Packet@{ub}
          The packet window. Supports the @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Close@{ub}, @{b}Activate@{ub}, @{b}Min@{ub},
          @{b}Max@{ub}, @{b}Front@{ub} and @{b}Back@{ub} commands.

    @{b}Fastmacros@{ub}
          The fast! macro window. Supports the @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Close@{ub}, @{b}Activate@{ub},
          @{b}Min@{ub}, @{b}Max@{ub}, @{b}Front@{ub} and @{b}Back@{ub} commands.

    @{b}Status@{ub}
          The status window. Supports the @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Close@{ub}, @{b}Activate@{ub}, @{b}Front@{ub}
          and @{b}Back@{ub} commands.

    @{b}Main@{ub}
          The main program window. Supports the @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Close@{ub}, @{b}Activate@{ub},
          @{b}Front@{ub} and @{b}Back@{ub} commands.

@{b}Result:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Warning:@{ub}
     -

@{b}Example:@{ub}
          /* Open all available windows. */

          WINDOW buffer review packet fastmacros status main OPEN


@EndNode

@Node "Attributes" "termRexx.guide/Attributes"
@Next "Wanted!"
@Prev "Commands"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}@{u}Attributes@{ub}@{uu}

   Several of the application's internal variables are can be accessed
and modified using the @{"GETATTR" Link "GETATTR"} and @{"SETATTR" Link "SETATTR"} commands. Information is
available on the objects and their associated fields explained below.
Each line consists of the object and field name and the type of the
available data:
@{b}Numeric data@{ub}
    @{b}<Object>.<Field>@{ub}
          Numeric

     The information is a numeric value.

@{b}Text data@{ub}
    @{b}<Object>.<Field>@{ub}
          Text

     The information is a text string.

@{b}Boolean data@{ub}
    @{b}<Object>.<Field>@{ub}
          Boolean

     The information is a boolean value and can be @{b}ON@{ub} or @{b}OFF@{ub}.

@{b}Mapped codes@{ub}
    @{b}<Object>.<Field>@{ub}
          <Value 1> ... <Value n>

     The information can be one of the given values.

@{u}The TERM object (read-only)@{uu}

@{b}TERM.VERSION@{ub}
     Text

     The `term' program revision.

@{b}TERM.SCREEN@{ub}
     Text

     The name of the public screen the `term' main window has been
     opened on.

@{b}TERM.SESSION.ONLINE@{ub}
     Boolean

     Whether the program is currently online or not.

@{b}TERM.SESSION.SESSIONSTART@{ub}
     Text

     Time and date when the `term' program was started.

@{b}TERM.SESSION.BYTESSENT@{ub}
     Numeric

@{b}TERM.SESSION.BYTESRECEIVED@{ub}
     Numeric

@{b}TERM.SESSION.CONNECTMESSAGE@{ub}
     Text

     The message issued by the modem when the connection was
     established.

@{b}TERM.SESSION.BBSNAME@{ub}
     Text

@{b}TERM.SESSION.BBSNUMBER@{ub}
     Text

@{b}TERM.SESSION.BBSCOMMENT@{ub}
     Text

@{b}TERM.SESSION.USERNAME@{ub}
     Text

@{b}TERM.SESSION.ONLINEMINUTES@{ub}
     Numeric

     The number of minutes the program is currently connected to a BBS.

@{b}TERM.SESSION.ONLINECOST@{ub}
     Numeric

     The cost of the connection to the BBS.

@{b}TERM.AREXX@{ub}
     Text

     The name of the ARexx host port the program is communicating with.

@{b}TERM.LASTERROR@{ub}
     Numeric

     The code corresponding to the error the last command has caused.

@{b}TERM.TERMINAL.ROWS@{ub}
     Numeric

     The number of available terminal screen rows.

@{b}TERM.TERMINAL.COLUMNS@{ub}
     Numeric

     The number of available terminal screen columns.

@{b}TERM.BUFFER.SIZE@{ub}
     Numeric

     The size of the text buffer.

@{u}The PHONEBOOK object (read-only)@{uu}

   Available fields are:
@{b}PHONEBOOK.COUNT@{ub}
     Numeric

     The number of entries in the phonebook. The single phonebook
     entries can be accessed as @{b}PHONEBOOK.0...@{ub} through @{b}PHONEBOOK.n-1...@{ub}.

@{b}PHONEBOOK.n.NAME@{ub}
     Text

@{b}PHONEBOOK.n.NUMBER@{ub}
     Text

@{b}PHONEBOOK.n.COMMENTTEXT@{ub}
     Text

@{b}PHONEBOOK.n.USERNAME@{ub}
     Text

@{b}PHONEBOOK.n.PASSWORDTEXT@{ub}
     Text

@{u}The SERIALPREFS object@{uu}

   Available fields are:
@{b}SERIALPREFS.BAUDRATE@{ub}
     Numeric

@{b}SERIALPREFS.BREAKLENGTH@{ub}
     Numeric

     The break signal length in microseconds.

@{b}SERIALPREFS.BUFFERSIZE@{ub}
     Numeric

@{b}SERIALPREFS.DEVICENAME@{ub}
     Text

@{b}SERIALPREFS.UNIT@{ub}
     Numeric

@{b}SERIALPREFS.BITSPERCHAR@{ub}
     Numeric

     The number of bits per transferred char. This can be either seven
     or eight.

@{b}SERIALPREFS.PARITYMODE@{ub}
     @{b}NONE@{ub} @{b}EVEN@{ub} @{b}ODD@{ub} @{b}MARK@{ub} @{b}SPACE@{ub}.

@{b}SERIALPREFS.STOPBITS@{ub}
     Numeric

     The number of stop bits to be used. This can be either 0 or 1.

@{b}SERIALPREFS.HANDSHAKINGMODE@{ub}
     @{b}NONE@{ub} @{b}RTSCTS@{ub} @{b}RTSCTSDSR@{ub}

@{b}SERIALPREFS.DUPLEXMODE@{ub}
     @{b}HALF@{ub} @{b}FULL@{ub}

@{b}SERIALPREFS.LOCALECHO@{ub}
     Boolean

@{b}SERIALPREFS.INTERNALXONXOFF@{ub}
     Boolean

@{b}SERIALPREFS.HIGHSPEED@{ub}
     Boolean

@{b}SERIALPREFS.SHARED@{ub}
     Boolean

@{b}SERIALPREFS.STRIPBIT8@{ub}
     Boolean

@{b}SERIALPREFS.CARRIERCHECK@{ub}
     Boolean

@{b}SERIALPREFS.PASSXONXOFFTHROUGH@{ub}
